<h4 class="article-subheader">Cocktail Hour</h4>
On my last trip to Seattle I purchased a
<a href="/traveler/2022_01-ski_trip/06-seattle?id=bartenders" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">book</a>
called "Where Bartenders Drink:
The Last Word on the Glass." One of the 5 listings for Oslo is just up the road
from the Akrobaten so stop at Himkok for a nightcap. Himkook (pronounced
*him-kook* & translates as "moonshine") is one of the earliest entrants to the
cocktail scene in Scandinavia. Their on-site distillery produces house aquavit,
gin, and vodka above a low lit barroom featuring dark wood, gilded mirrors, and
copper piping.

<figure class="figure container-fluid">
		<img class="figure-img img-fluid mt-2 rounded" src="/theme/images/traveler/2023_05-scandinavia/saetre_himkok_bar.jpeg" alt="Himkok bar">
  <figcaption class="figure-caption">I stole this photo from their website.</figcaption>
</figure>

The current cocktail program is inspired by traditional Norwegian sweet treats,
with offerings inspired by multekrem (whipped cream and cloudberries),
berlinerkranser (Norwegian Christmas cookies), and bl&oslash;tkake (cream cake).
Each of the 13 pages of the menu features a single ingredient such as plum,
blackberry, rhubarb, strawberry, apricot, cucumber, and a Northern European
staple, sea buckthorn.

